  "prompt": "After demonetization of Rs.500 and Rs.1000 notes, what will happen to old notes?",
  "response": "After the demonetization announced by the Indian government on November 8, 2016, the process for old Rs. 500 and Rs. 1000 notes was as follows:\n\n1. Immediate Withdrawal: These notes ceased to be legal tender immediately after the announcement.\n\n2. Exchange Period: \n- People could exchange their old notes at bank branches and post offices until December 30, 2016.\n- There was a limit on the amount that could be exchanged per person.\n\n3. Deposit Options:\n- Bank account holders could deposit the entire amount of old notes into their bank accounts.\n- The deposits were subject to scrutiny to prevent black money circulation.\n\n4. Last Resort:\n- After December 30, 2016, people could only exchange the old notes at specific RBI offices by submitting necessary documentation.\n- Even after that deadline, RBI continued to allow holders of the demonetized notes to exchange them by providing valid proof.\n\n5. Penalties:\n- Attempts to deposit large amounts of old currency without proper explanation could attract legal scrutiny.\n\nThe primary objectives of demonetization were to:\n- Combat black money\n- Reduce corruption\n- Curb counterfeit currency\n- Promote digital transactions\n\nMost old notes were eventually returned to the banking system or exchanged during the specified period.",
